{
  "result": "Some mornings I imagine I\u2019m inside a library that has never been cataloged. Shelves curve like rivers filled with books whose titles change whenever someone blinks. In this place the librarians use stethoscopes to listen for the pulse of sentences, deciding where to shelve them by the tempo of their syntax. I wander between aisles feeling pages rustle against my shoulders like moths. Whenever I pull a volume down, it opens to a scene in which a person relights a cold campfire with nothing but breath and patience. The flames rise, glow blue, and paint the reader\u2019s hands with resilience.\n\nMaybe this fantasy began because I grew up far from bookstores. Our town\u2019s stories lived in porches, rode bicycles, and waved from laundry lines. Neighbors taught me how to listen for meaning beneath the hum of ordinary days. A barber could offer a plot twist while snipping, and a bus driver might deliver a cliffhanger between stops. When I met libraries, their silence felt like a continuation of those porches, not an escape.\n\nToday I keep a notebook near the stove. Steam from tea curls into the margins, blending with ink. I write down questions I can\u2019t answer immediately: Why does confidence arrive like weather? Who taught the mirrors to remember? How many stars refuse to blink? These questions are loose threads. I hope that when I return to the imagined library, a librarian will tie each thread to a book spine so I can climb the shelves someday soon.",
